name: Central London with Stunning Views!
description:
We've welcomed over 500 guests and received exceptional reviews from all. You can be certain that our listing is 100% accurate and of outstanding quality.

We really enjoy hosting guests and you will love our central location and beautiful historical environment.
neighborhood_overview:
Our local area has an array of independent cafes, bars and restaurants, such as Fork, Casa Tua, The Norfolk Arms and the Marquis de Cornwallis, all on the edge of the West-End. We also have a renowned art-house cinema, The Curzon Bloomsbury, which shows award winning independent and foreign films.

You may also wish to enjoy a glass of champagne at the beautiful and historic St. Pancras Hotel, or a beautiful meal at one of the many up-market restaurants of Granary Square, such as Vinoteca, The German Gymnasium or Dishoom.

Equally, we're only a 5 minute walk to the Eurostar, should you wish to have lunch in Paris!

For those interested in history, the local area was developed by the Russell and Bedford families in the 17th and 18th centuries into a fashionable residential area. It's notable for its array of garden squares, strong literary connections and numerous cultural, educational and healthcare institutions.

host_about:
I'm a culture vulture... Art, music, opera, film, literature. I love it all! 

Whilst pursuing the arts and travelling as much as I can, I also live by the sea with my partner Akbar and our little Welsh Terrier, Teddy. 

We've been Airbnb hosts since 2009 and we've hosted over 500 guests from all over the world. We love it because we love meeting as many new and interesting people as we possibly can!

Good cycling, great local park with park run every Saturday morning and an outdoor gym!
neighborhood_overview:
I live in a friendly street, I know my neighbours and they know me - the local shop is run by my friend Puja who is kind, generous and really helpful - so if you get stuck ask Puja is I'm not around! NW2 is multicultural, vibrant, friendly and a great place to live. We have beautiful plantings of trees, iconic landmark sign of CRICKLEWOOD - you have to look up to see it - and fresh fruit, vegetables from all around the world. name: Lovely 2 bedroom flat near Brixton, zone 2, London
description:
Modern, luminous flat located between Brixton and Camberwell in London, zone 2. The flat has 2 double bedrooms, living room, kitchen, 1 bathroom with bath tub (which is ensuite to the main bedroom), 1 toilet with shower, 1 single sofa bed and all mod cons.
** Kindly note the price in the title is for the first 2 people, there's a supplement of £ 5 per person per night for the 3rd, 4th and 5th person staying
neighborhood_overview:
Brixton is a lively area famous for its Afro Caribbean market and has more recently seen a growing number of trendy restaurants and cafes - it boasts the best pizza in London (Franco Manca) according to Time Out. It also hosts the Brixton Academy famous for its concerts and there's a lovely cinema too, the Ritzy.

If you fancy staying in the area some evenings, we recommend the Cambria Pub or the Sun Pub, and if you want to have a stroll to Camberwell (10 minutes walk) both the Tiger and the Bear are worth a visit - plus there's a fantastic Chinese restaurant (very unassuming from outside) called Silk Road - spicy and nothing like your usual sort of Chinese food.

The flat is conveniently located to reach Vauhxall, London gay mecca, easily and quickly. Via tube, Vauxhall is just two stops away from Brixton; or by bus from Camberwell it's approximately 15 minutes away - see "directions" for details.

If you also fancy to explore a part of London a bit off
host_about: We are a couple being together for 8 years. We work in architecture and video-making and we love films, the arts, music, gardening, books, contemporary dance - and the occasional pint too!

name: Boutique Room w/ Private Bath, Balcony
description: Our modern, elegant, central apartment is part of a stylish development on a pedestrianised square in the vibrant and thriving artistic and hipster community of Dalston on the borders of Hackney and Islington - there are colourful East London markets (Broadway Market, Columbia Flower Market), amazing cafes and restaurants, quick transport connections to all the tourist sights of London. We are located just across from Dalston Junction station to ensure your comfort and safety night & day.
neighborhood_overview:
Dalston's high street is one of the most vibrant, colourful and authentic in London, with absolutely everything from pound shops to pharmacies to upmarket restaurants and cafes, as well as Ridley Road market (one of London's oldest markets) for colourful fruit.

Dalston Square is a pedestrianised area moments away from Dalston Junction Station, Cafe Route, the fringe Arcola Theatre, Vortex Jazz Bar, Cafe Oto, Dalston Roof Gardens, Farr's School of Dance, Sainsbury's, the community Eastern Curve garden, Ridley Road Market, and a short walk to Broadway Market. The Square itself has a great cafe (Cafe Route), an upmarket Spanish restaurant (La Ventana), a spa (Smooth You), Dalston library, an excellent vegetarian called Mildred's, and a neighbourhood supermarket (Coop).

Our apartment overlooks the square, and is quiet for its central London location, as well as being bright because we are on the higher levels. It truly is a serene, elegant space - very well-connected
host_about: Friendly, eclectic, relaxed. Our home is your home - welcome. I have travelled the world in style and know how to be a great host. I'm originally from Canada, studied in Germany and have lived in London for over two decades. I adore this vibrant city and all the arts on offer, especially theatre, galleries, modern dance and jazz (Dalston has great jazz cafes). l have two very adorable older children and two picture-perfect Siberian cats. Our last amazing trip together was to Japan during the cherry blossom!

neighborhood_overview:
Imperial Wharf lies between two of London's most exclusive residential areas, Fulham and Chelsea. Set in 10 acres of parkland, with stunning riverside views, this award winning development has to be one of London's most sought after addresses. It's situated in a peaceful location on the North bank of the Thames, adjacent to the famous Chelsea Harbour development - and yet the stylish boutiques, restaurants and cafes of the Kings Road are only a short walk away. For groceries you can walk to a Tesco supermarket within one minute a Sainsbury hypermarket within ten minutes. The Boulevard has a number of restaurants and a riverside pub.

A tree-lined, Mediterranean style boulevard lies at the heart of Imperial Wharf, and is brimming with shops, bars and fine restaurants such as Me Love Sushi, Wimbledon Wine Cellar and Saran Rom. neighborhood_overview:
Fitzrovia is a very desirable trendy, arty and foodie top location, in the heart of the West End in Central London. It's a wonderful and safe area with lots going on. Walk to tourist London or use the close by tubes. Head in any direction for a great day out. Amazing choice of restaurants, pubs and supermarkets.

The neighbourhood has a villagey feel and some beautiful Georgian architecture. It was was once home to such writers as Virginia Woolf, George Bernard Shaw and Arthur Rimbaud. Today Fitzrovia is a popular and lively neighbourhood with a residential and business mix. The numerous media companies based in the area feed into a vibrant buzz.
host_about:
We are Liz and Jack.  We manage a number of holiday let properties in Fitzrovia, central London and Lymington, as well as many long let properties. We look forward to welcoming you one of our super  home from homes.

We know Fitzrovia well and can thoroughly recommend it for its central London location, great transport links (although you'll probably be mostly on foot as tourist London is very walkable!) and wide choice of bars and restaurants. It's a highly desirable neighbourhood with beautiful architecture and interesting streets. People come from all over London to enjoy some Fitzrovia life. We're lucky enough to be based here and hope to see you here too! 

When we want to head out of the city, Lymington is our favourite getaway location. You'll love this quaint seaside town on the edge of the beautiful New Forest. 

We have been letting our properties for over 15 years. We hope we've perfected a warm and professional welcome. Really importantly, you can book with us worry-free. As you'll see from our vast number of reviews, we offer a friendly, guest-focused, helpful and absolutely reliable service.  

We're very happy to help with questions (before or during your stay) or to tailor any trip to suit your needs so just let us know if there's anything we can do. We look forward to seeing you in London or Lymington!

neighborhood_overview:
Shepherds Bush itself is a prime real estate location. It is among one of the most diverse neighbourhoods in London with convenience stores and multi ethnic restaurants just around the corner from the house.

Shepherds Bush is one of London best linked transport hubs giving guests easy access to Central London, the major airports, North, West and South- West Britain.

Shepherds Bush Green is a short walk or even shorter bus ride away from our home and is a bustling metropolitan centre with market, theatres, cinemas, music venues, gyms, night clubs, and the massive Westfield Shopping Mall with its comprehensive shopping ranging from Tiffany to Marks and Spencer, Prada to the Disney Store.

The BBC Television Centre is also just around the corner with its new high end restaurants, Soho House and TV studios. The London College of Fashion and the University of The Arts is also based in Shepherds Bush making this area popular with media types and fashion folk

Situated in the vibrant North London suburb of Golders Green, the area offers a rich blend of cultural diversity and green spaces. Golders Green boasts a variety of kosher restaurants, bakeries, and cultural centres, reflecting its rich heritage.

For nature enthusiasts, Golders Hill Park is a local gem featuring landscaped gardens, a small zoo, and a butterfly house. Adjacent to the expansive Hampstead Heath, visitors can enjoy woodlands, meadows, and panoramic city views.

The Hill Garden and Pergola, a hidden treasure, offers a serene escape with its beautiful architecture and seasonal blooms.

The area is well-connected, with Golders Green Underground Station on the Northern Line providing easy access to central London. The bustling high street is lined with an array of shops, cafes, and eateries offering global cuisines.

neighborhood_overview:
Peckham itself is a vibrant and fashionable area, and there are plenty of good cafes, bars and restaurants across the area. Peckham is thhe London neighborhood that has been voted one of the coolest in the world.

Frank’s Café on Rye Lane, provided the gold standard for the Peckham renaissance. Open every summer, it occupies the top floor of a former multistorey car park, welcoming children and dogs with alacrity, and staff hand out blankets on chillier evenings.

The six storeys beneath Frank’s host Peckham Levels, which are open year-round: a galli­maufry of international cuisine (mezze platters, Hawaiian poke, vegan pizza), a yoga centre, art and ceramics studios and Ghost Notes, a live-music bar. Tickets for the latest Hollywood releases and independent films at the ground-floor Peckhamplex cost a mere £4.99, less than half the price of cinema admission in London’s West End. All in all, perhaps the absolute best use of a used car park anywhere, ever...

neighborhood_overview:
Dalston is part of the borough of Hackney, in East London, and it's the place to be for artists, musicians, designers and the whole of London's creative industries. Even the Guardian has recently described it as "the coolest place in Britain".
It's been undergoing a huge regeneration, due to its proximity to the Olympic area (only 4 stops away), and it now boasts lots of trendy cafes, restaurants, music venues, theatres and an art house cinema; if that wasn't enough, Shoreditch and Hoxton are just 10 mins away.
The lovely London Fields park is also only a 10 mins walk away.
If you're looking for an exciting time in London Dalston is definitely the place for you, but if you're not so keen on partying it will accommodate your needs too as the residential streets like mine are extremely quiet and perfect for some relaxing time.

name: Charming Room in Restored Church
description:
My space is a unique blend of history and modernity, located in a peaceful area of West London within a reconverted church. This flat offers a rare combination of architectural charm and contemporary comfort, making it a truly special place to stay.

The living room features an original stained glass window as well as two beautiful arches that preserve the charm of the building’s history.
neighborhood_overview:
Over the past 10-15 years, Hackney has changed a lot. It used to be very poor, and indeed there still is a lot of poverty in places. But it is a vibrant, interesting neighbourhood, with a multi-cultural vibe, people of many ethnicities, plenty of families living here, and lots going on. It retains its 'urban grit' and cool edge.

We are located in travel Zone 2 which means not right next to the busy, noisy tourist traps, but in a place where it's fairly quick to get to central London and there is the space and beautiful garden instead! The full postcode is E9 6DW so you can see for yourself.

New cafes, bars, pubs and clubs have been springing up on our doorstep for some years or so and there are lots of nice restaurants nearby if you don't always want to travel into town. There are also City Farms, museums, and lovely walks along the canal and River Lea just 15 minutes' walk away.

I have enjoyed making my home comfy, quirky, cute & funky - I hope! I love living in my area of Hackney and very much enjoy welcoming guests to my place to enjoy London as much as I do. I hope I can show you the fun stuff that locals find and help you soak up the atmosphere. I have travelled to a few places in my time such as Iceland, Sri Lanka, Romania, Canada, Denmark and my favourite: South of France, but really I am a home girl at heart!

neighborhood_overview:

neighborhood_overview:
Bethnal Green is an exciting neighbourhood in the heart of London's East End. It's multicultural and diverse, full of energy and creativity but with a traditional core. There's no shortage of shops, food outlets and clothes markets nearby, as well as lovely parks, museums and also restaurants and clubs.
It's a family friendly area but also ideal if you want to go out in the evening, with trendy Dalston and Shoreditch nearby.
Bethnal Green is on the Central Line of the underground and really well connected with the city centre: it takes just about 15 minutes by tube to Oxford Circus and around 5 minutes to Saint Paul's cathedral, from where you can easily access the river Thames and the Tate Modern gallery of contemporary art. The number 8 bus will also take you to the centre via the City (the financial centre and Roman Londinium).

neighborhood_overview:
Located in Zone 2 (North London, between Finsbury Park and Manor House underground stations) and between two lovely parks Finsbury Park and Clissold Park next to Stoke Newington Church Street with lovely cafes and many vintage shops. Either self-cater or eat out at one of the many exotic restaurants just around the corner and down the road with many choices – Mauritian, vegetarian Indian, Indian, Thai, Caribbean, or Turkish, Italian, Greek and more! neighborhood_overview:
Hackney is a very vibrant, diverse and fashionable area with a thriving arts scene and amazing independents shops, restaurants & gastropubs serving fabulous food.

In good weather, there are some great green spaces to relax or picnic in including London Fields park which also has one of London's remaining outdoor heated lido swimming pools.

The flat is also a few minutes walk away to Broadway Market which is famous for its Saturday food market and antique stalls.

On Sundays, you can walk to London's famous Columbia Road Flower Market which is perfect for coffee and people watching before heading to Spitalfield's famous covered market for a spot of shopping and lunch from one of the many restaurants.

Bloomsbury is home of the British Museum, the largest museum in the United Kingdom, and several educational institutions, including University College London and a number of other colleges and institutes of the University of London as well as its central headquarters, the New College of the Humanities, the University of Law, the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art and many others. Bloomsbury is an intellectual and literary hub for London, as home of world-known Bloomsbury Publishing, publishers of the Harry Potter series, and namesake of the Bloomsbury Set, a group of British intellectuals which included author Virginia Woolf, biographer Lytton Strachey, and economist John Mayna

description:
Situated on the 9th floor of a brand new development with a concierge, this spacious apartment has 2 double bedrooms, 2 bathrooms (1 en-suite), an open-plan kitchen-living area, and a private balcony with seating.

The apartment comes equipped with cooking utensils, pots and pans, all kitchen appliances, bed linen & towels, high-speed internet and a smart TV with all your well-known apps.

The closest station is Willesden Junction (Overground & Bakerloo), just a 10-minute walk from the building.
neighborhood_overview:
Compared to other London places it's really quiet here, you will hear the geese and ducks and people rowing on the canal. We live in a Cul-de-sac and there will be kids playing outside in the afternoon. Generally, it's a very safe community and a brilliant close-knit neighbourhood in our street.

Our place is located in north-East london, right in the middle of the Hasidic Jewish community. Generally, Hackney is one of the most diverse places in England. There is a large Turkish community (lots of yummy kebab shops), Polish, Afro Caribbean and many others.

There are a few big supermarkets in walking distance (Sainsbury's and Asda) and many small local shops just a few hundred yards away (most of them won't be open on sabbath though)

If you're brave, rent out a bike and explore the area, it's well worth it. Or go for endless walks around the marshes and the canal.
host_about:
Hi, 
we are a couple in our mid 50's with a 12 year old daughter. I am German and my husband is of Irish origin. We love having guests and friends over and enough space to accommodate them.

We like getting around London on our bikes, shopping on flea markets and restoring old things. Tom is working full-time and I am working from home, running a vintage and antiques online business and website.

I had loads of lodgers in my old flat in Germany and it was always fun to meet new people.  We use Airbnb also for our travels and always had thoroughly enjoyable experiences.

Murielle, Tom & Alice

neighborhood_overview:
A bit of history about the W14 area:
Comprising parts of Fulham, Hammersmith, Shepherds Bush, Holland Park and Earls Court, it seems only right that four of London's busiest west-east roads pass through here and all are bisected by an equally busy north-south route. Equally appropriate is the proliferation of hotels and boarding houses, ancillaries to the twin monoliths in the area, Olympia and Earls Court Exhibition Halls. Covering all standards of accommodation, they are perhaps the sole unifying element of this postcode. Facilities in W14 are very much geared for visitors. Slap bang in the middle of W14 is the cavernous Kensington Olympia, built in 1884 and able to supply a gargantuan 37,000 square metres of exhibition space split between its three constituent halls. In recent decades it has had to play second fiddle to the even larger Earls Court Hall - just over the border in SW5 - but with both places now owned by the same firm the two quite happily complement each other.

neighborhood_overview:
We are located in a unique, diverse neighbourhood in zone 2 of the city centre. It has a rich heritage of its own and is well worth exploring, including Cockneys, Suffragettes, Kray Twins, the oldest fashion market in London. Nowadays there are local restaurants, cafes (try the local pie 'n mash), markets, galleries, boutiques and events and the market still exists.

We are close to many parks and canals and I really recommend exploring these by bike or by foot (Bow has been been nominated for a National Walking Award and Victoria Park has a Green Flag award).

For your shopping delight Stratford's Westfield Shopping centre (the largest indoor in Europe) is across the park to cater for your every shopping need. We are also within easy reach of the West End - Oxford circus and Covent Garden - by bus or tube.

We're ideally located to explore Shoreditch and Spitalfields, with its wonderful markets, hip lifestyle and nightlife. Lauriston village has hip cafe
host_about:
Hi, 

We're a fun, creative family living in London - a cultural fusion with roots in Sweden, Wales and West Africa. We travel quite a bit to visit family, to work or to further flung places when we can. Martin is a music, film and media producer with many a song or entrepreneurial idea brewing. I work in art, tech and design. I'm also an amateur painter and you'll see a few of my paintings dotted around the house. With a young child following in our footsteps it's a challenge to keep up with our multiple interests =)

Our home is comfortable, peaceful, child friendly and arty. We like some luxuries in life.

neighborhood_overview:
Hackney is one of London’s most dynamic and diverse neighbourhoods, known for its creative energy, vibrant nightlife, and rich history. Located in East London, this trendy area blends old and new, with historic architecture standing alongside modern developments, independent boutiques, and thriving markets.

Culture & Community:
Hackney has long been a hub for artists, musicians, and creatives, making it one of the city’s most exciting places to explore. The area is home to renowned theatres, art galleries, and live music venues, including:

Hackney Empire – A historic theatre hosting comedy, drama, and live performances.
EartH (Evolutionary Arts Hackney) – A cutting-edge venue for music, film, and culture.
Victoria Miro Gallery – Showcasing contemporary art from emerging and established artists.

Parks & Green Spaces:
Despite its urban edge, Hackney boasts some of London’s most beautiful parks, offering a peaceful retreat from the city

Stroll along the Thames Path, unwind in Southwark Park, or explore local cafés, gastropubs, and riverside restaurants. neighborhood_overview:
A bustling residential area of Rotherhithe, Surrey Quays is home to the largest marina in London, leisure facilities and a convenient shopping centre in the heart of Canada Water. The first dockyard on this part of the Rotherhithe peninsula was built in 1696, a manmade network of canals, timber ponds and docks heaving with ships. Canada Water is the only freshwater lake in Docklands, once forming part of Canada Dock. Pockets of Victorian streets, pubs and some sought after 19th century warehouse conversions recall the area’s history, but the docks were almost wiped out in World War II and subsequently closed in the early 1970s. The area was redeveloped in the 1980s and the overriding feeling is modern.

There are gorgeous walks and cycle rides to be enjoyed in both directions along the river and two Thames Clipper docking points, so many of the Canary Wharf workers who call this area home commute by boat. Those having a go at kayaking at the watersports centre here will find

host_about:

You'll get a warm welcome on JESSIE.

neighborhood_overview: We are located in the intersection between Hackney, Bethnal Green and Shoreditch. neighborhood_overview:
Chelsea is known for its beautiful houses with affluent residents and the upmarket shops and restaurants that cater to them. It’s a cultural haven too, with the Royal Court Theatre on Sloane Square and the Saatchi Gallery on the Duke of York Square.

You can walk to Harrods, Buckingham Palace and Hyde Park.

The red-coated retired soldiers known as the Chelsea Pensioners reside at the Royal Hospital Chelsea and form one of the area’s most iconic visuals.

Finally, if you’re a sports fan, then no trip to Chelsea would be complete without a visit to Stamford Bridge, the home of Chelsea Football Club. Either get tickets to a big game or take a tour of the stadium on non-match days.

Not to mention this is where Made in Chelsea is filmed.

If you get a chance, visit Pavillion Road for a coffee at The Roasting Party or a spinning class at KXU's boutique fitness studio.

neighborhood_overview:
Kilburn is a North West London neighbourhood. We are in Zone 2.
Kilburn has since the Roman times been a place a passage, Kilburn High Road being an old Roman road. It is multicultural and enjoys a very varied and busy high street, where as some say “everything and anything can be found”. Kilburn high road used to be the biggest shopping and entertainment street in Victorian times. We have shops and eateries catering for all tastes, from the first Primark shop in London, to TKMaxx for example. The Tricycle, a very successful cinema/theatre, is minutes from the house. Kilburn is also home to the “State”, now a church that was the biggest cinema in the world. It is opened to the public on Wednesdays. Within walking distance is a nice park if you enjoy a run and are travelling with children. If you like pubs, there are 5 within 5 mins walk. If you prefer a less busy atmosphere then West Hampstead and Queens Park are minutes away.
host_about: I am French and have lived in London for the last 25 years. I have traveled a lot and am used to receive guests in my house. I am more than willing to share my knowledge of London and am looking forward to meeting new people, who can feel at home here in Kilburn.

neighborhood_overview:
If you're looking for the best places to eat, drink, shop and explore in London, Hoxton and Shoreditch are the top choices! Hoxton is a vibrant and fiendly area in the London Borough of Hackney, situated just north of the City of London (financial district). It has a great community feel, with local pubs like the Howl at the Moon on Hoxton Street offering a welcoming atmosphere.

Shoreditch and Hoxton are often confused as they have a historical link and were both part of the Metropoitan Borough of Shoreditch in the past. However, Hoxton is more residential than Shoreditch, making it an ideal place to live and mingle with locals.

The southern half of Hoxton is now a hub for arts and entertainment, with plenty of bars, nightclubs, restaurants, and art galleries to explore. The area centres around Hoxton Square, a beautiful park surrounded by former industrial buildings and the elegant 19th century parish church of St John's.

host_about:
Hello fellow traveller,

 I am a seasoned traveller and know what it's like to find decent and reasonable accommodation in foreign lands! I have found that staying with the 'locals' gives you a wonderfully unique and rewarding prospective of new cities and places..  I have lived in Rio de Jeneiro, Brazil, and have travelled to India, Australia, Indonesia, Bali and Hawaii.  In New Zealand I stayed in a wonderful 'Home stay' and also in a tee pee in a national park.  I once run a small hotel in Cyprus, so I know how to make sure that my guests get the best out of their stay with me.

I am social, with good boundaries, and like to keep a tranquil home, I love cooking and am rather good at it, I just applied for next years Masterchef, 
I enjoy camping and have my own camper-van, nothing beats sitting round the campfire, gazing at the stars, and sleeping under canvas.
I am , writer a 'Life coach' , NLP Master Practitioner and Reiki healer. We have a lovely calm dog  'Yogi' , who is a very friendly non moulting breed- poodle springer spaniel mix. He is not allowed into the bedrooms. 

The house is clean and tidy, and we are a friendly, helpful and joyful bunch.

I am easy going, enjoy interior design, and love meeting new people, i make my own soap, and creams and am into a healthy eating, and organic food.

My hope is that our guests will enjoy, the friendly atomosphere of our home, and perhaps become life long friends of ours.
I look forward to making your staying with us unique and informative.

East Dulwich is locally nicknamed Nappy Valley with independent shops abound and where you'll find French pastry cafe's, delis, organic butcher and fish mongers as well as 'Yummie Mommies' pushing prams. Furthermore the area is full of pubs and restaurants and other places to hang out. Walking to diverse Camberwell along historic Camberwell Grove you will pass the Grand Union pub with its armchairs and chandeliers and onto Camberwell where you will have many economic ethnic eating options, an excellent tapas and unusual Chinese restaurant and many buses heading in all directions.

A short walk in yet another direction from the apartment will take you to Bellenden Road in Peckham Rye with restaurants such as Ganapati (South Indian cuisine), the Victoria Pub and Melange Chocolate, a quirky shop with a French owner selling hand-made chocolate in all varieties. You may have to s

Photography and art are big hobbies of mine and I also have a virtual shop where I sell my own handmade jewellery and cushions and shawls I design. Other hobbies: nature and reading and if able to combine these, I'm in paradise!

neighborhood_overview:
SUPERMARKETS AND FOOD STORES

Rochelle Canteen Delicious, one of our favourites. On Arnold Circus, it’s just before Club Row - there’s a black gate door and you press the top right buzzer (it’s marked) to be let in.  In the summer there’s a large lawn for kids to run around on.


Rochelle is a sister restaurant to St John’s Bread and Wine on Commercial Street in Spitalfields. It can be a bit noisy so ask for a “quiet” table. When we first moved to Shoreditch 21 years ago, we had to walk to Bread & Wine to get a coffee now the area is flooded with baristas.

Joelene on Redchurch Street - is great for takeaways - yummy sandwiches and coffee. 

Allpress is across the road and also ok, but Jolene winning at the mo. 

Leila’s on Calvert Ave - just around the corner from Arnold Circus - is a cafe and next door her grocery shop.

It’s also quite expensive but the produce is wonderful. If you like Smoked Mackerel - get it

neighborhood_overview:
Our neighbourhood is in the Borough of Lambeth, stretching from the South Bank of the river Thames to the suburbs of Streatham and Norwood. Lambeth is bursting with exciting attractions. Brixton, one of the borough's most multi-cultural areas has a thriving shopping centre and market. Its vibrant night-life makes it the heart of London's urban scene, and it also has the best live venue in London, the O2 Academy.

Another part of the borough, Kennington, is famous for the Oval Cricket Ground, where county and test cricket matches are played. Famous local residents have included Charlie Chaplin - who was born in Kennington in 1889 and Vincent van Gogh who lived on Hackford Road from 1873 to 1874.

neighborhood_overview: The North London "village" of Belsize Park is between Hampstead, Camden Town and Primrose Hill. You'll also find trendy cafes along Englands' Lane. It's round the corner from us. In the lovely "Belsize Village," just up the road, there are many good restaurants & cafes and a wine bar set around a square.  Our nearest small supermarket is 5 mins walk away.  Many guests appreciate the calm atmosphere of Belsize Park.  Fancy a walk or a jog? While there's no park in Belsize; Hampstead Heath is just a 10–15 minutes walk.  Or, Primrose Hill, where if you're lucky, you'll spot some of our local celebs jogging or chilling out, is a 15 minutes walk. It also offers some of the best views of Central London. Hackney is the place to be.... :) Although it's changed a lot in the last few years, there's still so much going on I hardly need to go into central London for anything! (Apart from work!)

host_about:
Well..I'd say I'm a bit quirky (my friends wonder at my humour sometimes haha!)

I absolutely love London, and I get a real pleasure seeing guests check out the area and liking it too  :)
I'm a practising Catholic (don't worry.. My best friend is gay and I don't pass judgement on any one!) and when I'm home I tend to catch up on various projects like sewing or sleeping (my second favorite hobby).
My long term boyfriend is currently in the States so I also spend time chatting to him on the phone :)
I've been an Airbnb host for almost 10 years now (my oh my that went quick!) so I've pretty much seen every type of situation. I also do Airbnb myself so I also know what it's like to be a guest, wanting a nice host, so I hope I fit the bill on that one.

neighborhood_overview:
Kynaston Road is located just moments from the superb amenities of Stoke Newington Church Street famed for its villagey atmosphere. Local attractions include a buzzy restaurant scene, a large local park 5-minutes walk away (Clissold), as well as a well-equipped local leisure centre with squash courts, 25-metre pool, gym and other facilities.

Just across the road is the newly restored Prince pub selling craft beers and fabulous food as well as a lovely cafe called Esters, famous locally for delicious flat whites, tasty homemade cakes and brunches. There is also a very handy grocery shop selling bread, milk, newspapers, beer etc. which is open from early till late every day.

Stoke Newington is one of the few remaining "villages" of London. Our local high street is populated with independent shops, bars and restaurants and has a unique, feel that you simply don't get in busy tourist areas. It's a place where many young families choose to live because it's safe, cle

neighborhood_overview:
The London Borough of Tower Hamlets is a vibrant and diverse destination that offers a unique blend of history, culture, and modernity for tourists to explore. Located in the heart of East London, it is home to some of the city's most iconic landmarks, such as the Tower of London and Tower Bridge. The borough's rich history can be experienced through its charming streets, historic buildings, and bustling markets like Brick Lane, renowned for its multicultural atmosphere and delicious street food. Tower Hamlets also boasts an impressive array of parks and green spaces, including Victoria Park, perfect for strolls or picnics. The borough is a melting pot of cultures, with a vibrant arts scene, museums, and galleries showcasing diverse artistic expressions.

The apartment is conveniently located near Brick Lane, offering an abundance of dining options and vibrant bars in the vicinity. You'll also find the renowned Carpenters Arms right across from the building.

neighborhood_overview:
Camden is one of London’s most iconic and distinctive areas. A huge player in the rock, punk and Britpop scenes of London’s last 40 years, this historic neighbourhood is known for being the stomping ground of many musicians, artists and writers. It’s not all about music, though: whether you’re looking for shopping, eating, or a great night out, Camden has it. Whether you’re a rocker, cool kid, metalhead, hippy, vintage queen or muso, you’ll find something to delight you in this fun part of North London!

The moment you step outside the tube station, Camden attacks the senses. Bass thumps from the market stalls' speakers, the scent of street food and incense permeates the air, and goths, punks, pushers and tourists shove past, giving the area an unorthodox charm. Camden Market has been one of the main draws of Camden for decades. Sprawled under arches and down cobbled alleyways, the market attracts those looking for alternative fashion, accessories, music and merchandise. Ther

host_about: Born In London within the sound of Bow Bells (that's very important ;)) I moved to Ireland where I grew up and where most of my family still lives. I returned to London in my early 20's and have lived between both every since.  I love to travel, most recently Canada which is a mecca for food "I didn't know that".  I plan to revisit South America  and tick more places off as soon as I can, it's vast and I need to explore it all.  I also have a half baked plan for a Camper Van odyssey around Aus/NZ one of these days. I love experiencing new cultures and places, chatting to global souls and visiting the local haunts with my camera taking memories and cooking and tasting the food.  I am a photographer, writer, musician,  interiors, architecture and design freak and sometimes a Program Manager/Analyst Programmer/Troubleshooter who likes meeting new people, learning new skills, exploring and stepping outside of my comfort zone.  I love to stay with locals when I travel as it gives you a different experience and makes you feel more part of a place. I love London and I try to welcome all of my guests and make them feel like they are at home, a local if you like!.  I have walked all over London and love to guide people to hidden places, so if you have any questions about my hometown then feel free to ask, I will try my best to furnish you with the answers.  I seek to make my guests experience of London and UK special, whether you are a solo or a couple of traveller(s) all are welcome.  My house is not a hotel, it’s a home and I open it up when I can to allow others to experience local London.   So if staying here sounds like your bag then I look forward to meeting you sometime soon ;).

host_about:
Hello there,

Large double room in quiet two bedroom end of terraced house in Sydenham (zone 3).

The house has good access to public transport; about 12 min walk to rail stations and London Overground.  The train from Sydenham Hill will take you to London Victoria in 15 min and the train from Sydenham will reach London Bridge in 20 min. You can park your car in the front of the house free of charge as there are no parking restrictions around the Sydenham area.

I am working Monday to Friday office hours and I am quite busy in the evenings so you will not see much of me.  I am happy to give you tips and info on places to go and how to get there if I can.

Any questions feel free to ask!

host_about: Heyia! My name is Laura and I am a German Photography student currently studying and living in London! I moved here more than 3 years ago and am now in my last year of studies! Plus jumping on a train at St Pancras and arriving in Paris just over two hours later is pretty exciting and all the new parks, squares, shops and buildings look amazing and all to be completed by 2015. It really is the best most vibrant area to be in London right now
host_about:

Roge is a theatre technician with Stomp in London's west end (we can get you free tickets upon request!) and I am co-founder and artistic director of Spymonkey Comedy. We spend time touring abroad so home is a very relaxed place to be due to often busy schedules.

We both love going to the cinema and have a particular passion for documentaries. Roge plays football and recently completed the London Marathon. I love to cycle come rain or shine. Roge is a fantastic cook and when the weather is good we have a penchant for bbq's on the terrace. 

We have a great bunch of friends and occasionally invite folk over for dinner and always invite the guest who is staying with us. In fact everyone who has stayed with us are now friends which is lovely.

I am also passionate about the theatre and regularly go to see all types of shows if I am not performing myself

We are really happy to answer any questions and make your stay as wonderful and comfortable as possible

host_about:
***ENHANCED SANITISING PROTOCOL FOR YOUR COMFORT. ***
Kia orana! (Greetings in Cook Is)
I'm a personable and passionate gay guy born in The Cook Islands  of paternal Scottish heritage with a proud collection of various tartan Kilts & Sporrans.
Mostly raised in beautiful Aotearoa - New Zealand.Lived in London since '89...I strive for a positively pro-active lifestyle...ex professional dancer & graduate of NZ School Of Dance. A member of Limbs Dance Company (Phone number hidden by Airbnb) 
Free-lance Fashion Archivist,Massage Therapist as well as organising fundraising events for a HIV charity.
Dancers discipline helps me maintain a reasonable fitness level by cycling and various gym workouts. 
Enjoy socialising with friends at theatre shows,Art Exhibitions or simply dining out.
Recently discovered the pleasurable benefits of infusion teas though I haven't as yet out grown my fondness for luxury chocolates. 
Travel feeds my insatiable soul and desire to challenge one's perceptions of the world at large.Curiosity of cultures fascinate me hence my prime reason for hosting guests...off the top of my head in no particular order...music, jewellery, contemporary art, Buddhism, dance, fashion, Gin, photography, current affairs, anthropology, sport, cinema, architecture, history, theatre, flying, concerts, floral & fauna, Art Deco and cuisine stimulate and satisfy senses.

neighborhood_overview:
Kilburn is a lively and diverse area in northwest London, known for its rich history, bustling high street, and excellent transport links. Straddling the boroughs of Camden and Brent, Kilburn offers a mix of old and new, with charming Victorian architecture alongside modern developments.

The heart of the neighbourhood is Kilburn High Road, a bustling thoroughfare lined with independent shops, cafes, pubs, and restaurants offering cuisine from all over the world. It's a hub of activity with a strong Irish, Caribbean, and Middle Eastern influence, reflected in the food, culture, and music of the area.

For entertainment, the Kiln Theatre is a must-visit, hosting thought-provoking plays and independent films, while the historic Gaumont State Cinema (now a church) remains a striking local landmark. Green spaces like Kilburn Grange Park and nearby Queen’s Park provide a perfect escape for a leisurely stroll or a morning workout.

description:
This apartment comes with 3 bedrooms spaciously accommodating up to 6 -8 adults easily. It features a large living room with a sofa bed and a full kitchen with essential cooking utensils. It has two bathrooms which come with a bath tub and a shower. Underground car parking space is available , subject to availability. Advance reservation is required.

neighborhood_overview:
It is unique in so much as it is so close to the centre of London, but has a real feel of peace, quiet and country side. It is close to the river, where I regularly do a 7K run around the 2 bridges loop (takes about an hour to walk this), and Bishops Park is 5 mins away which has a lovely Farmers Market every Sunday morning. There is a great local pub, The Crabtree, on the river 5 mins walk away and a great little corner shop for all your basic shopping requirements. The famous River Cafe Restaurant is about a 10 minute walk away along the river and I can recommend many others.

Jump on a bus at the top of the road and you can arrive at the great museums of South Kensington within 20 minutes and Piccadilly Circus is 15 minutes on the tube once you get to Hammersmith.

name: Beautiful Family Apartment
description: Welcome to our spacious and stylish apartment in Shepherd’s Bush, one of London’s most vibrant and family-friendly neighborhoods. This well-equipped flat offers two comfortable bedrooms, two modern bathrooms, a fully equipped kitchen, and a cozy living space, perfect for families, friends, or business travelers. Enjoy easy access to Westfield Shopping Centre, parks, restaurants, and excellent transport links for exploring London. Book your stay today!
neighborhood_overview: This has become one of the most desirable neighbourhoods in the last five years because it feels like a village set within the metropolis of London. We are just around the corner from a park called London Fields and the ever popular Broadway Market which has restaurants, shops, bakers, butchers and a fish monger plus a fantastic Saturday market for food. There is a year round heated outdoor pool in the park and plenty of playgrounds for the kids. Our own street has two fantastic coffee shops, a Borough Wines shop, two great pubs, two convenience stores and a great hairdresser (the street has featured in the Times and The Guardian). We are moments away from a great cinema The Hackney Picture House and the Hackney Empire Theatre, which has great drama, comedy and music shows. We are also a short walk to all the shops in Hackney Central for all your other needs. There are two supermarkets just around the corner and plenty of convenience stores.
host_about: We are both artists (but not crazy and messy!) and like staying in interesting places. We often go out dressed the same without planning it, and we wish we had more time to do nothing!

neighborhood_overview: Also known as the Square Mile, the City of London is the historic financial district with medieval architecture and modern amenities. This furnished flat is located within walking distance of several banking headquarters, such as NatWest and RBS. There are plenty of dining and drinking options to take you from an early morning grab-and-go breakfast to late business dinner. In the evening on weekdays, there are a plethora of stylish restaurants and top-quality bars and pubs at which to socialize. On weekends, when the city slows down, there are great cultural attractions to enjoy, such as the Barbican, Europe's largest multi-purpose arts space. The City of London is very well-connected with local tube stations, for example Bank, Monument, Cannon Street and St. Paul’s stations are within minutes of your apartment.

neighborhood_overview: Wimbledon, a leafy and affluent suburb of London, offers a unique blend of urban convenience and green spaces. Enjoy a leisurely stroll through Wimbledon Park, renowned for its beautiful lake and recreational facilities, or explore the historic Wimbledon Village, home to charming boutiques, cafes, and pubs. For tennis enthusiasts, a visit to the All England Lawn Tennis Club, the iconic home of the Wimbledon Championships, is a must. The area also boasts a diverse culinary scene, with restaurants offering a range of cuisines to suit all tastes. In Wimbledon Chase, you'll find excellent local pubs, such as the ever-popular The Sultan, and dining spots like the highly regarded San Lorenzo, offering authentic Italian cuisine.

neighborhood_overview:
Clapham is a varied, vibrant area of South London comprising of a huge Common, and a long High Street. Due to the area's size, as you'd expect, there's a great deal of variation in pretty much everything. It has an appealing mix of good transport links, urban character and plenty of attractive period homes which make it one of the most flourishing and sought after parts of south London. Shopping, transport connections and the social scene make it a truly fantastic place to stay. Clapham residents from all walks of life are united by the eponymous Common. Despite being surrounded by busy arterial roads, it is a broad and tranquil green space beloved by all locals. A focal point for the community, all manner of sporting events and activities take place, as well as annual events including the popular SW4 festival.

BLOOMSBURY: LONDON'S LITERARY AND CULTURAL HEART

Welcome to Bloomsbury, one of London's most distinguished and culturally significant neighborhoods. Steeped in literary history and intellectual heritage, this elegant district offers a unique blend of academic prestige, cultural riches, and urban convenience.
History & Character

Bloomsbury's beautiful garden squares, Georgian townhouses, and tree-lined streets create an atmosphere of refined tranquility amidst central London's energy. Once home to the influential Bloomsbury Group of writers and intellectuals, including Virginia Woolf and E.M. Forster, the area retains its scholarly ambiance thanks to its numerous academic institutions.

neighborhood_overview:
Many things. Clapton is great. I don't want to use the phrase "up and coming" because everyone says that about many areas of London, but there are some great pubs, bars, cafes and restaurants in the local area, and you can travel some short distances to find more, such as in Dalston, Hackney central or Stoke Newington - and slightly further, Shoreditch.

Chatsworth Road, only 10 mins walk away, has a great Sunday market, many stalls, food, antiques and various stuff, and some great places to eat and drink.

I'm also very close to the Lea Valley and Walthamstow Marshes, which has some great walks down the river, cycling, or jogging if you need somewhere to run to or around. I even believe you can go horse riding.

Very happy to answer questions about this, and to recommend place to eat or drink.

We love living in East Dulwich with our small son, Mattias. We are happy, busy people into travel, meditation, complementary health, good food and wine and walking. We have both travelled extensively and some of our happiest travel memories involve meeting local people and getting to experience a place in the ways that they do!

neighborhood_overview: Where I live is Tower Gardens Estate  which is a distinctive semi-circular estate bounded by Lordship Lane and the Roundway.  Constructed between 1904 and 1928, it was one of the first municipal "cottage estates" in the world.  It is now a conservation area and was featured in the annual London Open City architecture weekend. It is one of the first "garden suburbs" in the world and is characterized by good quality and practical buildings that show an inventive use of materials and vernacular motifs typical of the Arts and Crafts Movement. Along with Hampstead Garden Suburb, Tower Gardens is one of the most important estates of its type in London.  These houses when built have lots of little interesting architectural features which differ with every street.  The trees lining the streets are protected and provide a boulevard feel, particularly Risley Avenue, privet hedges to the front fascia of the properties within the conservation area are protected and give it more of a rural atmosphe

The Abney Park Cemetery, once a nonconformist graveyard, is now a beautiful green nature reserve, full of wildlife and a perfect place for a walk, a run or some dog-spotting. Nearby, Clissold Park features a full lake and a deer enclosure. St. Mary’s Old Church is a simple yet beautiful 16th-century building that often holds events and services. If you want to shop like a local, then don’t miss a trip to Meat N16 which is a traditional butchers shop, and Little Pad is great for vintage clothes. neighborhood_overview:
If you're looking for the best places to eat, drink, shop and explore in London, Hoxton and Shoreditch are the top choices! Hoxton is a vibrant and fiendly area in the London Borough of Hackney, situated just north of the City of London (financial district). It has a great community feel, with local pubs like the Howl at the Moon on Hoxton Street offering a welcoming atmosphere. Shoreditch and Hoxton are often confused as they have a historical link and were both part of the Metropolitan Borough of Shoreditch in the past. However, Hoxton is more residential than Shoreditch, making it an ideal place to live and mingle with locals.

The southern half of Hoxton is now a hub for arts and entertainment, with plenty of bars, nightclubs, restaurants, and art galleries to explore. The area centres around Hoxton Square, a beautiful park surrounded by former industrial buildings and the elegant 19th century parish church of St John's.

name: Queen’s Park Flat
description: This newly refurbished Victorian flat above a coffee shop is 20 minutes from central London via Underground. A 20-minute walk takes you to Portobello Road/Notting Hill. Located in Queen’s Park, known for its village-like charm, restaurants, a farmers market, and a beautiful park. The flat features a bright open-plan living room, modern kitchen, tiled bathroom, and quiet double bedroom. Fast Wi-Fi and streaming services included. Owners live in the separate flat above. 2 minute walk to the tube.
neighborhood_overview: Kings Cross is transforming in front of our eyes! I love everything about this area: the surprising leafy squares, the access to everything - on foot! - the location is astonishing.
host_about:
Hello! I'm Aleks. I'm originally from the US but lived in the UK for 20 years. I was in London for three of those, and absolutely love this city.

I also love this flat! It's so close to The Guardian newspaper offices (in the dynamic and delicious Kings Place venue on Regent's Canal), where I was the host of Tech Weekly, their technology podcast, for eight years, and where I have written columns and features about the social implications of the web. My first book was published by Guardian Books in (Phone number hidden by Airbnb) , and is called Untangling the Web: What the Internet Is Doing to You.

The flat is also only 20 minutes away from the BBC on Regent's Street, where you can hear The Digital Human, a series on Radio 4, about who we are in the digital age.

It's also a 15 minute cycle ride to the LSE, where I was a Visiting Fellow in the Media and Communications department researching the little things the web assumes about us when we use sites like (Hidden by Airbnb) and (Hidden by Airbnb) . For it, I created something called The Serendipity Engine.

I'm a foodie, and love to cook. You can tell this by the cookware I have in the kitchen :) I am a big fan of the new branch of Caravan in the fabulous Granary Square around the corner, and love the street food revolution that's epitomised by _KERB, which is open around the corner every weekday on Kings Boulevard. My favourite restaurant in London, though, is a vegetarian joint, Mildred's in Soho.

I also love exploring this city, using books like Richard Barrett's Medical Walks of London or Peter Ackroyd's London: A Biography as a guide.

I'm currently in Brooklyn, working and living in a whole new city and time zone. 

I'm a voracious traveller; I was born in Malaysia to Polish-American parents, grew up in New Orleans, spent five years living just outside LA (though it's where most of my family still live), went to high school in Washington D.C., and college at Oberlin, in Ohio. I moved to the UK because I fell in love when I was studying abroad in Glasgow, Scotland. That relationship didn't last, but my love for the country remains.

I've lived in Glasgow where I learned to drink beer and eat haggis. I've lived in Leamington Spa near Birmingham in the Midlands where I discovered great curry and the cycle paths and canals that criss cross the country. I lived in Guildford where I got my MSc and PhD in Social Psychology. I've lived in Brighton where I began to play beach volleyball competitively on the national tour. And I lived in London, where I ran on the canal, ate good food, consumed local culture and generally loved the view. I've also done stints in Florence, Italy and Paris, France. Next up: Paris again. Or Tokyo for the (Phone number hidden by Airbnb) Olympics. Who knows? The world is our oyster.

neighborhood_overview:
The Camden Markets are a number of adjoining large retail markets in Camden Town near the Camden Road Lock of the Regent's Canal , often collectively named "Camden Market" or "Camden Lock". Among products sold on the stalls are crafts, clothing, bric-a-brac, and fast food. It is the fourth-most popular visitor attraction in London, attracting approximately 100,000 people each weekend.[1] A small local food market that has operated in Inverness Street since the beginning of the 20th century has lost stalls since local supermarkets opened, and as of 2010 this market retains only three fruit and vegetable stalls (which are closed on Sundays), in addition to stalls for other products. Since 1974 a small weekly crafts market that has operated every Sunday near Camden Lock has developed into a large complex of markets.[2] The markets have a mixture of temporary stalls and fixed premises.

Brimming with art galleries, independent shops, museums, Michelin-starred restaurants, and lively bars, Notting Hill offers an irresistible blend of culture and charm. Just a short walk from Hyde Park—one of London’s four royal parks that stretches from Kensington Palace to Buckingham Palace—this location is ideal for exploring the city. Whether you're strolling along the dreamy canals of Little Venice in Paddington or browsing through local markets, there's something here for every taste. host_about:
I am a professional  artist and art history lecturer and divide my time between a nearby studio in the Chocolate Factory N16, and working freelance as art history lecturer with a regular job at the National Gallery where you could come on one of my regular guided tours.

Some of my work takes me abroad and I had been commissioned in the past by galleries to travel to places such as India, Israel, Morocco, Australia, as well as the length and breadth of the British Isles, to prepare an exhibition.
Or I might work as guest speaker on a river cruise and so had struggled with names of Hungarian artists on the Danube or spoken about German art on the Rhine.


My love of art and travel means that I like my surroundings  be beautiful and interesting And I enjoy sharing my home with others.

I am a warm and welcoming person who takes an interest in others. I care about another's wellbeing and always try to resolve their problems and help with their anxieties. I smile quite a lot!

Bounds Green is mixed Cosmopolitan community with fantastic tube and transport links. Nearby there are acres of sports fields and conservation-areas which is great for families as well as being ideal for young professionals, students and tourists - there is something for everyone!

Situated between Muswell Hill, a hilltop village with many boutique shops, cafes and restaurants and Wood Green with its busy shopping malls and cinemas, it is also within walking distance of Alexandra Palace and has the A406 (north circular) virtually on the doorstep.

Many shops are open 24/7 as are cafes and take aways which are open late so, this is not an area where you will go hungry - there is something for everyone whatever your taste or your nationality.

There are also traditional bars and pubs within walking distance of the apartment.

neighborhood_overview:
Tottenham forms part of the Borough of Haringey lying within Greater London one of the world’s largest conurbations.

Tower Gardens Estate is a distinctive semi-circular estate bounded by Lordship Lane and the Roundway and is a conservation area created in 1978. Constructed between 1904 and 1928, it was one of the first municipal "cottage estates" in the world.

The estate occupies a special place in history as one of the world’s first garden suburbs. It consists of low rise and almost entirely residential buildings, and possesses high architectural standards. Most of the estate (the whole southern side, and part of the northern side), was designated as a Conservation Area by the Council in 1978.

description: Great location with easy access to transport and motorways. Quite neighbourhood with plenty of green all around.
neighborhood_overview:
My neighbourhood is great in that it is really close to lots of the main attractions of London without being crowded with tourists, but at the same time there are plenty of places to eat, drink and buy groceries on my doorstep.
It is quite good for arts and culture because it is in the South Bank area of London. Some of the places within 20 minutes walk include the London Eye, the Tate Modern, the Houses of Parliament, Somerset House, the Royal Festival Hall and the Imperial War Museum.
What it doesn't really have is any clothes shops, but if you want to go to Oxford Street or Covent Garden it only takes 15 minutes by public transport.
If you want to relax there is a small park a minute's walk away but two larger and nicer parks about 10 minutes' walk away. Also it's only 15 minutes to Green Park by the Underground.
If you want to buy food there are lots of options close by, including two small supermarkets (Sainbury's Local and Tesco express) and a great grocer.

description: Welcome to this beautifully presented three-bedroom home, blending character, comfort, and modern living. neighborhood_overview:
The area:

Our flat is in the neighbourhood of Brockley, New Cross and Deptford, in southeast London zone 2, in the Lewisham Borough Council. It is close to both Goldsmiths, University of London (7-minute walk from our flat) and Brockley village (13-minute walk) with arty cafes and chic bars for you to choose from morning to late night.

Apart from students at Goldsmiths, University of London and establish artists living in Brockley village, Deptford market has formed a new art community too.

Trinity Laban (an arts centre and a higher education institution offering performing arts degree courses) is in Greenwich, not far from our flat. Also, Rose Bruford College (main campus in Sidcup, about 30-minute drive or 1-hour by public transport from our flat) has a Lewisham College campus, which is walking distance to our flat.

The market place in Deptford is a multicultural place, so is New Cross and Lewisham in whole.

My partner and I, and our cats, share our cosy flat with guests and we hope you will enjoy your stay here. name: Homely 4BD House near Tower Bridge and The Shard
description: Nestled in the vibrant and trendy Bermondsey area, this charming four-bedroom house will be your home away from home during your stay in London! Within walking distance of Borough Market, Tower Bridge, and The Shard, you will be surrounded by renowned bars, restaurants, and galleries, immersing yourself in the city's iconic sights and rich history. With excellent transport links nearby, the city’s vibrant sights are at your fingertips, making it easy to explore everything London has to offer!
neighborhood_overview:
Once an important part of London’s river trade, Bermondsey sat derelict for several decades, until the area’s wharves were renovated in the 1980s. Now it’s a lively part of town, with some exceptionally good restaurants and coffee houses, although they can sometimes be a bit tricky to find. Bermondsey also has plenty of excellent bars and pubs, usually packed to the brim with visitors and regulars. Bermondsey can turn Londoners into tourists: The Scoop in particular attracts both out-of-towners and locals to its free quality events.

If you haven’t already, make sure to take a stroll down Bermondsey Street to see what one of London’s most ancient streets has to offer. From the Bermondsey Street Festival to the Bermondsey Antiques Market, this street continues to thrive. I couldn’t recommend this area enough – and I'm not just saying that because it’s my home.

host_about:
I love reading, my fave book is David Copperfield.  Anything by Dickens. Hardy, Thackery. Love playing tennis if you can't find me that's where I'll be. I play the piano and sometimes it's available for guests to play.  I enjoy music by Debussy fave is Claire De Lune, and Rachmaninov though I only listen to his stuff its too hard for me to play!
I am a retired psychotherapist. I loved working with people seeing them healing and growing their self esteem .
I enjoy movies and usually go once a week if not more. I enjoy thrillers such as 'Taken'  but also enjoy a more gentle tale. Life of Pi was a remarkable yet beautiful film which I enjoyed more than the book.
As a host I am warm friendly and welcoming.  As a guest I'm considerate and respectful. 
My favourite travel destination is New York such an exciting vibrant city. For a more carefree sunshine holiday I love Spain, or France.  The farthest I've traveled was to Australia to visit relatives a long time ago so may go again. I thought Sydney was pretty cool!   Enjoy cooking if I'm in the mood but sometimes I let someone else do the cooking! I'll eat almost anything I'm not a fussy eater! But I do enjoy smoked salmon with champagne! Sea food love it!  I enjoy the theatre and opera and ballet.  All time fave is Romeo and Juliet with music by Prokofiev and choreography by Kenneth Macmillan I weep through most of it!!!! And as for the opera well it has to be Madame Butterfly or Tosca.

name: Edgy & Designer Camden Town Apartment
description: A gorgeous designer apartment, set in a modern converted warehouse building, in the heart of Camden Town.
neighborhood_overview:
Eclectic, vibrant, and brimming with character, Camden Town is one of London’s most iconic and culturally rich neighbourhoods. Famed for its alternative spirit, Camden offers a unique blend of historic charm and modern edge. The area is a haven for creatives and music lovers, with legendary venues like the Roundhouse and Electric Ballroom just a stroll away.

By day, explore the bustling Camden Market, where street food stalls, vintage treasures, and independent boutiques line the canalside. By night, the atmosphere comes alive with live music, buzzing pubs, and atmospheric bars. For those who crave green space, the expansive Regent’s Park and the panoramic views from Primrose Hill are just minutes away. Camden Town is perfect for those who want to immerse themselves in London’s bold, artistic energy while staying well connected to the rest of the city.

neighborhood_overview:
Hackney is one of London’s most diverse, creative and historic boroughs. It has more green space than any other inner-London borough including Haggerston Park, London Fields, Hackney Marshes, and more. Diversity has created a thriving cultural quarter all around Hackney with theatre, cinema, festivals and a cutting edge music scene and nightlife.

The famous Hackney Empire puts on a wide variety of entertainment including plays, children’s pantomine and opera. The Rio Cinema is one of the few independent and community run cinemas in the country; and of course there is Sutton House – a Tudor hunting lodge restored by the National Trust is located in Homerton.

If you cannot find your favourite food in Hackney then you’re not trying. There are food stores and restaurants from almost every part of the world. neighborhood_overview:
Paddington, unlike other central areas like Marble Arch and Oxford Street, has maintained a peaceful charm, with most visitors coming only for the Heathrow Express at Paddington Station. The area offers quiet streets, independent cafes, good schools, and even the two-month-long Paddington Festival. For shopping and cafe culture, Oxford Street and Marylebone are nearby, while the canal and Hyde Park offer tranquil escapes. Paddington is ideal for those seeking central living with a lively yet relaxed vibe.

Just a short distance away is Notting Hill, one of London’s most iconic neighborhoods. Known for the vibrant Portobello Road Market and its world-famous carnival, Notting Hill offers a blend of culture, history, and charm. Explore colorful terraces, antiques shops, historic pubs, and street food, or enjoy the people-watching and the public art on Portobello Wall. The neighborhood is lively on weekends, but visiting on quieter weekdays gives a perfect opportunity for cycling

neighborhood_overview: East Dulwich is full of proper, lovely independent food shops (cheese, bread, fish, organic produce etc) and cafes/restaurants. If you don't know it, London is a really massive, sprawling city, and East Dulwich is a relatively central 'inner-city' suburb in South London, a proper neighbourhood with all the benefits that brings! It has lovely parks nearby and a nice relaxed feel to it, while also being very close to the city. It has become very popular in the last few years with young professionals and families and feels safe and easy. The shops are a strong point and there is a very strong community of independent traders, selling everything - wonderful cheeses, chocolates, clothes, furniture, bread, jewellery, lampshades, meat, fruit, gifts, cards, wine. I also love its proximity to pretty and very smart Dulwich Village (with the wonderful Dulwich Picture Gallery) and also its proximity to lively, multicultural Peckham, which is a real hub for artists and creatives too.
host_about: I work in the theatre industry, but when I'm not working I'm very happy to be lazy and domestic! I love London and have lived here for 14 years, so am happy to give any advice I can. I'm friendly, but self-sufficient and independent, like cooking, film and have bookshelves full of things if you're stuck for something to read during your stay.

Belgravia is one of London's most prestigious and sought-after neighborhoods, known for its timeless elegance, charming cobbled streets, and sophisticated atmosphere. Located just south of Buckingham Palace and close to iconic landmarks such as Westminster and Knightsbridge, Belgravia is a hub of luxury and refinement.
The area is renowned for its beautiful Regency-style architecture, with grand townhouses, white stucco facades, and leafy garden squares that provide a serene, private environment. The tree-lined streets are quiet and peaceful, yet you are just moments away from the vibrant energy of London’s cultural and commercial centers.
Belgravia is home to some of the city’s wealthiest residents, including diplomats, celebrities, and high-profile professionals, contributing to the neighborhood's exclusive, cosmopolitan feel. The area offers a range of upscale boutiques, art galleries, and fine dining establishments, as well as proximity to world-class shopping destination

neighborhood_overview:
About Fitzrovia London

Fitzrovia is an inner London neighbourhood. The district is frequently described as having a bohemian history, upmarket and home to some celebrities. Media reports often describe the area as “trendy”, “glamorous” and “swanky”,
Neatly tucked away between the wealth of Marylebone, the edgy energy of Soho and the grandeur of Bloomsbury, Fitzrovia is peaceful and attractive, home to small media organisations, small pubs and small restaurants and a smattering of decent hotels. Wide streets lined with tall buildings in Victorian brick mingle with cosy side alleys, with a variety of architectural styles from the eighteenth century to the present day, all of it dominated by the BT Tower, one of London’s tallest and most iconic buildings. Tottenham Court Road is the major shopping street, and the best place in London to look for home furnishings and electronic goods. Why Stay in Bloomsbury? The Perfect Base for Exploring London

Bloomsbury is one of London’s most charming and historic neighborhoods, offering a unique blend of culture, elegance, and convenience. Known for its beautiful garden squares, world-class museums, and literary heritage, it provides a sophisticated yet welcoming atmosphere for visitors.

A Cultural and Historical Gem
• Home to the British Museum, one of the world’s most famous cultural institutions.
• Rich literary history—once the heart of the Bloomsbury Group, including Virginia Woolf.
• Stunning Georgian architecture and tranquil garden squares provide a picturesque setting.
• A vibrant mix of independent bookshops, cafes, and art galleries, perfect for relaxed exploring.
